WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.800
Hello, my name is Colin Rundel, and today I'm going to tell you a little bit about a

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:12.200
package I've been working on recently called parsermd.

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:16.480
This package implements a parser for R Markdown documents using the Boost Spirit library in

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:22.160
C++ and exposes a series of functions and data structures that allow for the manipulation

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:26.320
and evaluation of R Markdown documents from within R.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:30.799
So to give you a little bit of context, I teach large statistical computing courses

00:00:30.799 --> 00:00:35.520
and I deliver assignments to students in the form of R Markdown documents.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:39.040
These R Markdown documents have very typical structures, so they have things like YAML

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:44.240
at the beginning, section headings to keep bits and pieces organized, instructions in

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:50.080
the form of Markdown text, and then various code chunks that include either example code

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:53.680
or areas where we want students to enter their own code to implement a solution or something

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.080
like that.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.360
And this works really, really well, except one of the difficulties we have is that the

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:03.439
documents contain lots of boilerplate in the form of these instructions or demo code that

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:07.080
we don't actually care about when it comes time to mark it and actually distracts from

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:09.480
the content that we are really concerned with.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:14.000
And so part of the motivating reason for developing the parsermd package was a desire to be able

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.400
to take these kind of documents once the students have turned them in and then strip out all

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.480
of that boilerplate to get down to just the stuff that we actually care about.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:26.360
And so today I'll show you some examples of what that looks like in practice.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:32.120
So at its core is this parse underscore rmd function, which reads in our Markdown document

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:35.639
and then turns it into a simple abstract syntax tree.

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:39.040
And so for our purposes right now, we don't really need to understand what that is.

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:44.360
But the key thing to see is all of those elements we just saw in that homework01.rmd are here.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.839
So we see that there's the YAML is represented.

00:01:46.839 --> 00:01:48.760
We have the various section headings.

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:52.000
We have the Markdown text and the code chunks.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.720
And this is presented in a hierarchical way, but it's really just flat.

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:59.000
We're just inferring the hierarchy based on the various heading levels that we see within

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.440
the document.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:06.639
If this hierarchical view doesn't work for you, we can also turn this into a tidy rectangle

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:08.839
of data using the as-tbl function.

00:02:08.839 --> 00:02:13.440
And so what we now have is the same representation of that data where that AST has been wrapped

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:14.440
up into a tbl.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:17.360
We can manipulate things by looking at the various other columns that are there.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:20.160
But that AST we were just seeing is still here.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.440
It's now just in its flat form represented in that AST column on the right-hand side.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:27.639
So AST, what is that?

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:28.639
How do I work with it?

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:29.639
What do I care about?

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:33.399
It's a custom data structure, but it's really just a list of lists.

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:37.399
And it's all managed by S3, and it's not something that you actually need to worry about in practice

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:40.399
because the package implements a bunch of helper functions.

00:02:40.399 --> 00:02:44.660
So if we want to subset for various elements, so in the example I have, I care about the

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:46.320
exercises and the solutions.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.679
So here I can use the subset function to pull out anything that matches exercises with

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:52.600
a wildcard and then solution.

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:57.679
So this gets me all of the nodes that belong to an exercise 1, 2, or 3, and then the various

00:02:57.679 --> 00:03:01.759
answers the students may have put into those particular bits of the document.

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:04.160
I can pull those out.

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:06.820
Once I've done that, I can then also manipulate the document further.

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:10.639
So a common issue students have is they may write code that has an error, and if we were

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:14.559
to try to knit that document, we would not be able to because of the error.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:17.919
So what we can do is we can then manipulate the code chunks to add new options.

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:21.880
So this is going to go through and set error equal to true for all of the code chunks so

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:25.119
that when we knit the document, it'll keep knitting even if there is an error at any

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:27.880
point in the document.

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:32.039
Once we've done that, we can then, say, turn the document back in text, or we can even

00:03:32.039 --> 00:03:33.600
just render it directly.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.320
So in this case, I could turn it back into an HTML document and examine it.

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:40.960
And so again, this makes it very easy to then take the student's code, pull out the pieces

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:44.360
I want, and then render just the solution so that I can then mark it much more easily

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:48.479
without all of that other sort of cruft around.

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:49.479
This works really well.

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:53.119
In practice, it's a little bit more difficult because we depend on the structure of the

00:03:53.119 --> 00:03:56.080
document matching exactly what we expect when we're extracting things.

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:58.679
And so one of the things that I've also done in practice with this that's been able to

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:02.960
be built on top of these tools is the idea of a template, an automatic feedback for the

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:03.960
students.

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:08.800
So an RMD template is just a simple representation of the nodes that we expect to find and the

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:13.160
various sort of labels and location references that we care about to indicate where they

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:14.160
are.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.760
And it's just a simple tibble that we can generate using the RMD template function once

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.000
we've subset it for the elements we want.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.679
And once we have that, we can then feed it into another helper function called RMDCheckTemplate,

00:04:24.679 --> 00:04:27.720
which we can then use that to compare against the student's work.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:30.880
So here I'm comparing against homework01-student.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:34.239
And we get a user-friendly error message out telling you exactly what's missing or what's

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:35.600
problematic about the document.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:39.959
So in this case, the student is missing something in exercise one and exercise two.

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:43.239
And they're told explicitly what that is, either a code chunk or markdown text or what

00:04:43.239 --> 00:04:46.380
it's particularly looking for in that context.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.679
And so this is something we're actually able to deploy to students this semester via GitHub

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:50.760
Actions.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.559
And if it's something that you're interested in, all of the example code, including the

00:04:53.559 --> 00:04:58.399
GitHub Action workflows, are included in the repo that I've linked at the bottom there.

00:04:58.399 --> 00:04:59.399
Thank you very much for watching.

00:04:59.399 --> 00:05:02.359
Additional details about the package are available on GitHub.

00:05:02.359 --> 00:05:06.799
And please let us know if you have any feedback on the package breaks or you have an interesting

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:07.799
use case.

00:05:07.799 --> 00:05:08.299
Thanks.

